<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2010/01/12/dm-server-project-moves-to-eclipse-org">dm Server project moves to Eclipse.org</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/689563c501d5a959fccf03b707cb7b13?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<span class="author">Adrian Colyer</span>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2010-01-12 11:10:00.0">January 12, 2010</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="302" href="/blog/2010/01/12/dm-server-project-moves-to-eclipse-org#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>Today we will be releasing version 2.0 of the dm server. This represents a major milestone for the project, and for enterprise application development with OSGi in general. I’m delighted to now be able to reveal the next step in the dm Server journey: we have submitted a proposal at Eclipse.org to continue development of the dm Server as part of the <a href="https://www.eclipse.org/rt/">Eclipse RT</a> top-level project. The Eclipse nickname for the project is Virgo.</p>
<p>Quick links:<br></p>
<ul>
<br>
<li><a href="https://www.eclipse.org/proposals/virgo/">Virgo proposal document </a>at Eclipse.org</li>
<br>
<li><a href="https://eclipse.org/forums/eclipse.virgo">Virgo community forum</a></li>
<br>
</ul>
</div>
</section>
